&lt;div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"&gt;
&lt;div class="prompt input_prompt"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="inner_cell"&gt;
&lt;div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;What is a quantum computer?&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A quantum computer is a machine that operates on quantum bits. But what does it mean to be &lt;em&gt;quantum&lt;/em&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Well, it means we are dealing with a probabilistic system in which bits can either be 0, 1 or both in a &lt;strong&gt;superposition&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Quantum computing holds a lot of properties:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When you try to make an observation, they stop being quantum and return to classical nature&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;They operate on a very very small scale, we can only see quantum nature in very small objects (photons, or electrons for instance)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Hold enormous power, 30 qubits = $2^{30}$ calculations&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Can have multiple subsystems (even classical subsystems)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;All operations are reversible&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;One operation can change all amplitudes&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Are able to optimize on some classical algorithms, for instance, factoring large integers: $O (b^3)$ in polynomial time as opposed to non-polynomial time on classical machines&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Quantum algorithms are formed from a problem that is probabilistic in nature and easy to check&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"&gt;
&lt;div class="prompt input_prompt"&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="inner_cell"&gt;
&lt;div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;$\newcommand{\ket}[1]{\left|{#1}\right\rangle}
\newcommand{\bra}[1]{\left\langle{#1}\right|}$
Perhaps that is enough to wet your appetite. Therefore I shall start from the very beginning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We can represent a quantum bit with the following: 
$\begin{matrix}
  1 \\
  0
 \end{matrix}$ = $\ket{0}$ 
 $\begin{matrix}
  0 \\
  1
 \end{matrix}$ = $\ket{1}$&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And also in a superposition: 
 $\begin{matrix}
  1/\sqrt(2) \\
  1/\sqrt(2)
 \end{matrix}$
 whereby both $\ket{0} or \ket{1}$ are both as likely&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As they are probabilistic, the squares of the amplitudes for a given qubit, equal one.
 $1/\sqrt(2)^2 + 1/\sqrt(2)^2 = 1$&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We should also state that amplitudes in quantum bits are represented by complex numbers&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered"&gt;
&lt;div class="input"&gt;
&lt;div class="prompt input_prompt"&gt;In&amp;nbsp;[1]:&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="inner_cell"&gt;
    &lt;div class="input_area"&gt;
&lt;div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;amplitudes&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;[]&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="n"&gt;NUM_OF_QUBITS&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;span class="k"&gt;def&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="nf"&gt;setupPsi&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;n_qubits&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;):&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class="c"&gt;# in this classical simulation, we will simulate a n-qubit system&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class="n"&gt;amplitudes&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mi"&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;*&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;n_qubits&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;                             
    &lt;span class="n"&gt;amplitudes&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="mi"&gt;0&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="mi"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span class="k"&gt;return&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;amplitudes&lt;/span&gt;
        
        
&lt;span class="n"&gt;amplitudes&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="n"&gt;setupPsi&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;NUM_OF_QUBITS&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="nb"&gt;print&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;amplitudes&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

